John Edward: language skills essential for world citizens
Scotland’s independent schools continue to be distinguished by academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with further outstanding test results and is only supported by individual and joint successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students from across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the highest possible level of care for their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and coveted as elective subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is an impressive reminder that we can not only rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s test results show that languages with the highest rates of existence are at the top of the independent school rankings.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages scored A at the higher exams.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of Mandarin students at higher exams scored A, while 72 percent of students who learned German, 69 percent of students who learned French, and 63 percent of students who learned Spanish also scored A.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now regarded as elective as STEM subjects (natural science, engineering, and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014, 17 percent of the reasons employers mentioned for the problems of occupying vacancies were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary when it comes to preparing young people for their future profession.
As more and more vacancies require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage in the future through such a lifelong skill.
To be able to communicate directly with people from other countries, multilingual people will automatically get a lead over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15%).
That’s why it’s important for today’s children to invest in language teaching now.
Children who speak multiple languages, especially languages in developing countries, will have better chances of finding meaningful employment.
Different languages are taught in all schools in Scotland.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other languages will be taught that are considered to be the most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever your child’s interests lie, a number of languages will always be available at independent schools with appropriately specialized teachers.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and provides them with the skills necessary for their success, whatever the future looks like.
At this point in time, in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should actually be regarded as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
We have to do it.
