Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a current U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim assured that he would work on “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the Korean war from 1950 to 1953, while the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes demands for a loosening of stringent international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘first denuclearization’ and increases the pressure of sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and is even against the ‘declaration of the end of war’,” Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can force us on our knees is a brain sensation of people who don’t know anything about us.
