Ri did not address plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. head highlighted earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party in the denuclearization issue instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to a standstill.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri’s speech was enormously different from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target North Korea’s missiles on the mainland of the United States after “the evil” President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who had threatened with North Korea’s “complete destruction” last year, praised Kim at the United Nations for his courage in terms of disarmament steps, but said that there is still much work to be done and that sanctions must remain in force until North Korea’s denuclearization.
