Harvard students learn enough to sleep in one course
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all students get more sleep in primary education this year, which is a measure against the spreading macho culture of keeping themselves awake with caffeine and learning throughout the night.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unnecessary when it comes to taking care of themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and is, in his opinion, the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to launch the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I not learning about it until now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
This year’s first course explained to the students how the basics of good sleeping habits contribute to academic and sporting performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the University’s health services, said the university chose to introduce the course after finding that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, students will see the picture of a room in a dormitory and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books, providing information on the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effects of sleep deficiency on sports performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes and cancer.
They are then encouraged to think about their daily routine using a map of the university site with interactive symbols.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know this – just like you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health,” said Czeisler.
The pride in pushing a “night layer” is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep deficiency a growing problem.
Ensuring enough sleep should be the “secret weapon” of all students against stress, fatigue and fear, he said, and weight gain could be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain into hunger mode so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler conceive the course. He had taken one of his courses in his first year at Harvard last year.
He said the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step all postgraduate students will be encouraged to complete a similar study program before starting their studies at the competitive university.
According to Professor Czeisler’s recommendation, students should make up a clock for sleeping time and wake-up time and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” that comes from electronic screens and LED lights and can take the circadian rhythm out of the clock, which leads to problems with falling asleep.
