National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research is being conducted at a property in the Scottish Highlands to show how bats use the landscape in food searching.
It is hoped that the results will enable further insight into the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide future nature conservation activities.
The study conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will track dwarf and mosquito flag mice, as well as the brown long ear and water flag mice in Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key positions on the property to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also carry out mobile investigations using portable detectors.
With a noise analysis of all recordings by experts, the frequency of the bats is determined and determines which species does what.
Subsequently, a map and a report of the habitat is created to create a detailed picture of their behaviour at the landscape level.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes that the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
These data will help determine the benefits of habitat management measures, such as meadow creation, and show how to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the whole of the United Kingdom has declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to loss of habitat.
Windshields and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as fly catchers and the chemical treatment of building materials or even attacks by home cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo location to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS responsible for maintaining more than 270 historical buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland takes the subject of bats very seriously.
He has 10 trained experts who regularly conduct investigations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even set up Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s 10 bat species.
Property administrator David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for them.
“Here in Threave we have a great area for bats,” he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there is a lot we don’t know about bats yet, so we are doing these works here and on other goods that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable.”
He emphasizes the importance of excluding the presence of bats before maintenance work in the goods, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single nest place could kill up to 400 females and young animals and wipe out the entire population on site.
Bats are under protection and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy them or their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
She explains: "We still have to learn a lot about bats and with many of our species we don't know what their populations are."
