Update on Red Tide: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota decrease
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, more gap flowering conditions are recorded, indicating decreasing concentrations.
A red algae flower stretches over about 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of the district of Lee.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough District, but at fewer spots compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In the past week, average concentrations in or off the coast of Pinellas district were reported, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Charlotte district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Lee district, and low concentrations in Collier district.
Respiratory problems continue to be reported from the districts of Pinella, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In northwestern Florida, no new respiratory problems have been reported over the past week.
